ce:section.ce:para:
In this paper, we found that, in the presence of H2O2 and HRP, DHB (such as o-DHB, m-DHB and p-DHB) could be oxidized to corresponding benzoquinone which could efficiently quench the fluorescence of GQDs. And the fluorescence intensity ratio of I/I
                     0 is proportional to the concentration of DHB. Therefore an ultrasensitive DHB detection method was developed based on GQDs (Scheme 1
                     ). This was the first example for DHB quantitative sensing utilizing GQDs as far as we know. Due to the excellent optical property and nanometer size effect of GQDs, the detection limits were much lower than the published optical and electrochemical methods. The present method could be used for the quantitative determination of DHB in rainwater and tap-water samples, and had a potential application for detecting various analytes which can be translated into benzoquinone in aqueous solution.
